{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11432"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.1,0.01,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4065"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"1969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4814"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to the sexual health clinic requesting sexually transmitted infection (STI) testing. Two days ago, he received an anonymous text notification stating that he might have been exposed to chlamydia. He is asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon further questioning, he had sexual encounters with three male partners within the past month. He practised receptive anorectal and oral sex and often forgot to use a condom. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His last sexual health screening was two months ago, with the results being negative for HIV, chlamydia, gonorrhoea, syphilis, hepatitis C, hepatitis A and hepatitis B.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First pass urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and lymphogranuloma venereum","Mid-stream urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and mycoplasma genitalium","HIV, syphilis serology and first-pass urine NAAT for chlamydia and gonorrhoea","Pharyngeal swab NAAT for gonorrhoea only","First pass urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia and gonorrhoea, HIV serology and syphilis serology"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a few clinical indicators for chlamydia screening in this case, including recent exposure to any STI within the past 12 months and personal request for STI testing. According to the Australian guidelines, subpopulations - which include men who have sex with men, pregnant people, sex workers - are also at increased risk of chlamydia infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor men who have sex with men, screening guidelines for chlamydia is for the 3 sites: \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst pass urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT chlamydia and gonorrhoea.\u003C/strong\u003E Patients who are asymptomatic may be able to collect the anorectal and pharyngeal (throat) samples themselves. It is also recommended to test for gonorrhoea at the same time and to perform appropriate contact tracing and notification.  Fifty to 75% of patients infected with chlamydia are asymptomatic; therefore, testing should not be dependent on the presence of symptoms. Australian guidelines also recommend performing 3 monthly screening for other STIs (HIV, syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhoea) for asymptomatic men who have sex with men. For this patient, he had recent negative HIV and syphilis screening only two months prior however has had a new STI thus may benefit from repeat screening earlier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst pass urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and lymphogranuloma venereum\u003C/strong\u003E includes testing for lymphogranuloma venereum (LGV), which is not routinely recommended for asymptomatic screening in Australia. LGV testing is typically reserved for symptomatic patients or in outbreak situations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMid-stream urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and mycoplasma genitalium\u003C/strong\u003E uses mid-stream urine rather than first-pass urine, which is less sensitive for STI detection. Additionally, routine screening for mycoplasma genitalium is not currently recommended for asymptomatic individuals in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV, syphilis and first-pass urine NAAT for chlamydia and gonorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate because it only tests for urethral infections via the urine sample. Given the patient\u0027s sexual practices (receptive anorectal and oral sex), testing should include all potentially exposed sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal swab NAAT for gonorrhoea only\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate as it only tests one site for one infection. Given the notification about chlamydia exposure and the patient\u0027s sexual practices, more comprehensive testing is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe screening guideline is also applicable for transmen who have sex with other men.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["50-75% of patients infected with chlamydia are asymptomatic.","3 monthly screening for STIs (HIV, syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhoea) is recommended for asymptomatic men who have sex with men.","Comprehensive STI screening for men who have sex with men includes first pass urine, anorectal swab, and pharyngeal swab NAAT for chlamydia and gonorrhoea."],"references":["ASHM Organisation. Chlamydia - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2021 [cited 20 December 2021]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia/","ASHM Organisation. Standard Asymptomatic Check-Up - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2021 [cited 20 December 2021]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/standard-asymptomatic-checkup/","ASHM Organisation. Men who have sex with men - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2021 [cited 12 January 2022]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/populations-and-situations/men-who-have-sex-with-men/","Levy SB, Gunta J, Edemekong P. Screening for Sexually Transmitted Diseases. Prim Care. 2019 Mar;46(1):157-173. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.10.013. Epub 2018 Dec 24. PMID: 30704656. Avaiable from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30704656/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T00:24:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T00:28:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":